Package cu.edu.cujae.graphy.algorithms

Interface Algorithm<T>

  • Type Parameters:
    T -
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    AbstractAlgorithm, BellmanFordShortestPath, BridgeFinderAlgorithm, ColorableAlgorithm, CycleDetection, DialShortestPath, DijkstraShortestPath, ExistPath, ExistSimpleRoad, HamiltonianCycleDetection, IsolatedVertices, KosarajuAlgorithm, MotherVertexFind, PrimMinimalTree, TreeDetection
    public interface Algorithm<T>
    An algorithm is a process or set of rules to be followed in calculations or other problem-solving operations, especially by a computer.This interface encapsulates the concept of algorithm for its use on this library. Algorithms are implemented as classes, taking an arbitrary set of input parameters but producing a well defined output. This output is defined by the parametrized type that this class takes. The user then after applying the argument can retrieve the result using the method get.

    Algorithms must be implemented in a way that they do not depend on the particular implementation of the graphs, therefore, heavy use of iterator classes is recommended.

    Author:
    Javier Marrero

    • Method Summary

      Modifier and Type Method Description
      Algorithm<T> apply()
      Applies the algorithm using some arbitrary input parameters (that must be provided elsewhere) producing an output that is latter recoverable.
      T get()
      Returns the result of the last execution of the algorithm.
